I cannot say enough how incredible the workflow and directions are for ML. I got Axon up and running and I am able to get some excellent results. We went to the ML workshop last year, and it was excellent, but there were some integral steps missing (I think it was the Amazon/Jupyter piece).

My preliminary tinkering (We have currently lost two build days to weather, so I felt it would be a good time to tinker away) has me thinking that this could really be useful for our team this season. However, I have a few questions.

  • If we want to use the premade and pre-labeled videos of the field, what do we do after we import them into supervise.ly? The tutorial has us split the video into images and then label them, but what if we are okay with the current labels?

  • If we have a dataset that has multiple labels (like the one above), how do we choose which labels we want to include in our training?

  • When we retrain the dataset, how do we determine which is the best Epoch to export? Do we want a higher or lower precision, or would the latest record be the most desirable?

  • If at the end of our retraining, the precision stays high (I am still not exactly clear on what is a good precision) like in the image below, should we retrain? Or, is it okay, but if the results are partially proficient, should we just make sure to annotate the dataset better?

image1629×759 70.1 KB

I got the above results using the Open image database. I wanted to see how well it would identify my dog, but not her stuffed toys. It is pretty good. It identifies her 100% of the time, but sometimes, it identifies her twice, and it does identify one toy and some carpet as a dog. All-in-all, I am so impressed with this, and it is going to be easy to teach this to the team.

As an aside, FIRST and the WPILib keep teaching me new ways to make my classroom accessible. The way they take complex concepts like this and make them approachable to students and mentors is astounding.
